## 5.4 - Other plotting considerations:
We can see even from a brief look at the plots that these implied volatility surfaces are very rough. This isn't necessarly a problem, as the arbitrage conditions regarding convexity and monotonicity we've stated only apply to the prices. However, these very rough surfaces may be an indication that the prices this surface would give may have arbitrage opportunities (both butterfly arbitrage and calendar arbitrage seem to be present). Furthermore, this isn't an artefact of some inaccuracy in our IV computation as the same behaviour appears when using yfinance's computed IVs (you can quite easily modify the above to check this for yourself). 

All hope is not lost. There are many other things one may wish to consider when producing sensible volatility surface plots to lower the chances of arbitrage opportunities and inaccuracies even when using a method that doesn't guarantee an arbitrage-free surface. Some things to think about include:
- Data quality in financial markets is imperfect and when data is missing we will sometimes get prices of 0 for the bid/ask/current price (which are clearly incorrect). This will wreak havoc on the model if they aren't checked and protected against. At the moment we default to the last traded price in these situations.
- The recency of data can have a big impact. In some cases the most recent price is quite old and would no longer be a sensible price (i.e. the underlying has changed value significantly since then). Furthermore, sometimes options are traded on a market with different trading times to that of the underlying, which can lead to prices for one being more recent than the other and making our implied volatilities incorrect.
- There are several options for which prices to use. One can use the bid, the ask, the midpoint of the bid and the ask and (for more liquid markets) the most recent price. One may also want to include information about the size of the spread as this is very important when considering arbitrage opportunities (even if a theoretical arbitrage may exist, if the spread is large it will not be profitable).
- If one uses the midpoint (as we have) it is  possible for there to be no arbitrage in the real market but an arbitrage opportunity may appear to exist when one looks only at the midpoints. For this reason it can make sense to ignore prices where the spread is particularly large.
- Similarly, out of date / incorrect option prices can lead to non monotonic prices as the strike/time to maturity changes (which is again quite problematic, as it also creates arbitrage opportunities)
- Some exchanges (For instance ICE, EUREX) send settlement prices - the price at which trading the asset closes / was last traded for. If they haven't had a trade in a few days, they may still provide a settlement price which is far from the trading price of similar options and would lead to an arbitrage if included.
- Using primarly out of the money options - If one uses in the money options, these have generally higher prices and larger spreads (making the bid vs midpoint vs ask vs most recent traded price choice much more impactful). We can see in some places our implied volatilities seem to be changing rapidly for different strike prices. One plausible reason for this is that some strike prices have call option data while others have puts, so when either the call or put prices are inaccurate, we get these poorly behaved oscillations.
- Exercise 13: Give another reason (involving computing the implied volatilities from a "correct" stock price) for why we may wish to not consider deeply in the money options. - Solution: There are machine precision issues for ITM options, and terms in the BS price get rounded to 1. Because of how floating point numbers are implemented in computers, these issues are not as prevalent for out of the money options where the values are near 0.

One possible extension activity would be use the above ideas and explore filtering which options are used to make our volatility surfaces in order to improve our results.

# 6 - Volatility Surface terms and properties
Some specific slices of the volatility surface are important enough in trading to have their own names and many volatility strategies may use only one aspect to determine the profitability of trades. We will also discuss some typical types of volatility surfaces and some typical behaviours.

## 6.1 - Volatility Skew
Volatility skew is the general term for the shape of the cross section of the volatility surface with a fixed time to expiry (strikes varying). Typically the words "Volatility skew" (also "negative skew" or "reverse skew") on their own refer to the case where we have higher implied volatilities for low strike prices than for high strike prices. The most common reason for this that investors are willing to pay a premium for put options to protect against large market crashes. Some trading strategies (including one that was in a coding session last year called VolatilityRiskPremium) involve selling these puts to take advantage of this premium as the strategies suppose that investors are overpaying out of fear of a big crash.


### 6.1.1 - Positive / forward skew
Another type of volatility skew is positive / forward skew. This, as you would expect, is the opposite of negative / reverse skew. Implied volatility for high strikes is higher than it is for low strikes. This suggests market participants are expecting a fairly sharp increase in prices, and are willing to pay a little bit extra to make a profit off of the increase. Positive skew is commonly found in commodities like gold and oil. One reason for this with gold and other "safe haven" assets is that in market crashes, people tend to buy gold and other precious metals. Oil, as well as other commodities that are needed to make other products, can have sudden demand surges where lots of people need them causing prices to rise suddenly which can also lead to positive skew.

### 6.1.2 - Flat / no skew
This refers to when the implied volatility is (roughly) the same across options. In these cases, investors expectations of future returns perfectly match the log-normal distribution that the Black-Scholes model predicts. This doessn't, however, mean that the volatility is similar to historical levels. Often changes in the overall height of the volatility surface can be as important as the shape.

### 6.1.3 - Volatility smiles
One common shape for the volatility skew to take is a "smile", with higher implied volatilities further from the strike price and lower implied volatilities closer to the strike. There are several plausible explanations for volatility smiles, including:
- Demand is higher for in / out of the money options than at (or near) the money ones, so they're more expensive and therefore have a higher implied volatility.
- Market participants expect a higher probability of "rare" market events (i.e. future stock prices follow a platykurtic distribution, a one with thinner tails than a normal distribution). Many modern option pricing models predict the true chances of "rare" market events as higher than that of Black-Scholes. They therefore have different (larger) estimates of the changes of a massive increase / decrease in price than the Black-Scholes model predicts leading to higher implied volatilities. 

One piece of evidence supporting the "market participants expect a higher probability of rare events" hypothesis is that before the 1987 crash, volatility surfaces were much flatter. After 1987, market participants realised that these "rare" events were much more common than the Black-Scholes model would predict and implied volatilities far from the strike increased.

Some research also suggests there is a relationship between how "strong" / curved the volatility smirk is and the future performance of the underlying. Also, if investors expect the underlying to perform poorly, they may buy OTM puts for downside protection (increasing the implied volatility for low strikes) and if they expect the underlying to perform well, they may buy OTM calls. Hence, the current volatility surface can give some indications of expected future performance.

### 6.1.4 - Inverted volatility smiles
In some (generally rarer) cases, implied volatility can be highest near the money and lower far from the money, leading to an "inverted smile" (or frown, but inverted smile is the more common term). There are some meaningful reasons for this:
- Market participants expect a lower probability of "rare" market events (i.e. future stock prices follow a platykurtic distribution, a one with thinner tails than a normal distribution)
- When a significant jump in stock price is likely to occur at a predictable time, inverted volatility smiles tend to occur. This is because the probability the stock being near its current price in the future is low, and it is more likely to be further from the current strike. Some real world examples of this include: 
    - When a pharmaceutical company has a drug that's about to finish the last clinical trial (if successful, the share price increases massively, if unsuccessful, the share price decreases massively)
    - When a large tech company is about to release an earnings report (if the earnings are good the price will jump up, if poor it will fall rapidly)
    - For large sectors of the market: when a large election (i.e. for the US president) is about to take place between candidates with very different views (i.e. one will bring harsh regulation and higher taxes, while the other promises deregulation and tax cuts)
    - For large sectors of the market: When the Federal Open Market Committee is about to release the interest rate announcement for the coming months
There are models devoted to determining sensible options prices prior to earnings announcements (and other big shifts of this nature). For instance [this paper](https://business.columbia.edu/sites/default/files-efs/pubfiles/6051/DJ_2006.pdf) discusses the improvements that can be made when one takes into account earnings announcements. 

More generally, jump diffusion models are used to get better prices for options both in cases of inverted volatility smiles and more generally. There are a range of different jump diffusion models and many involve too much stochastic calculus to be included here. For a more detailed review of jump diffusion models, see [this paper](https://www.columbia.edu/~sk75/MagSci02.pdf).


## 6.2 - Volatility term structure
This refers to how the implied volatility changes for different times to expiry with the same strike price. These can change based on lots of important information in the markets. For instance, the impact of a successful or failing drug trial can lead to higher implied volatility on options just after the trial than just before. Generally options expiring just after the event have a larger change in implied volatility than those expiring much later than the event. Several events can cause increases in implied volatility observable in the term structure including:
- US Treasury bills have increased volatlity just before short-term interest rates are announced
- Commodities like corn show increased volatility prior to the announcement of harvest forecasts

Volatility term structures can more generally be:
- increasing, so the market expects higher volatility far in the future than in the short term
- decreasing, the market exprects lower volatility far in the future than in the short term

In practice, the term structures are rarely truly monotonic, and whether a term structure is increasing or decreasing is determined by the general pattern. 

Some reasons for increasing volatility term structures include future supply disruptions (i.e. if there's an expectation of a large war in a couple months, and in this war one of the participants is a major oil exporter, the volatility of oil prices will be much higher in the future than tomorrow).

Far in the future implied volatilities are generally fairly similar to historic volatilities. One possible reason behind this gradual return to a more "normal" lower volatility is said to be because a stock cannot have extremely high volatility for a long time, and must eventually revert to it's historical mean. Therefore, if the current short term implied volatility is particularly high then the long term volatility should be lower than the short term and we get a decreasing implied volatility.


### 6.2.1 - Volatility structuce in trading strategies

The volatility term structure can be used to predict returns of stocks. For instance in [this paper](https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=1944298) a clear relationship is seen between the slope of the volatility term structure and future stock returns (although when implemented in practice, this may be significantly less profitable with all of the fees). We may look at this strategy in more detail in the session where we go through this document.

## 7.1 - Extensions for the session
The following extension activities are entirely optional. If there is enough time in the session, we may go through some or all of them:
- Filtering the options based on (some of) the criterion stated just after the last volatility surface plot. (See also: [this page on building reasonable volatility surfaces](https://tsimagine.com/insights/thinking-about-building-a-volatility-surface-think-again/)). This will hopefully make the plots look more reasonable, and reduce the chances of arbitrages occurring in our surfaces.
- Faster IV computations - it takes some time to compute IVs, so performance improvements would be worthwhile:
    - Experimenting with faster normal CDF computations (for instance, using some of the ideas covered in this paper: [Approximating the cumulative distribution function of the normal distribution](http://jsr.isrt.ac.bd/wp-content/uploads/41n1_5.pdf)).
    - Implementing the Hybrid Newton method for root finding discussed just before we implemented the Brent method, which is useful for implied volatilities as we have a closed form expression for the derivative.
- Different pricing models:
    - One alternative to the Black-Scholes model is the Bachelier model. This model assumes S_t is a normally distributed variable instead of a log-normally distributed one which leads to the possibility of prices being negative! This is generally seen as a downside, since stocks shouldn't have negative values. However, in 2020 oil prices dropped so sharply that for a time they were negative, and at that time some exchanges swapped to the Bachelier implied volatility instead of the Black-Scholes implied volatility. Fortunately, the Bachelier IV can be computed very quickly without an iterative algorithm. A great paper for further reading on the Bachelier model is this one: [A Black-Scholes user's guide to the Bachelier model](https://arxiv.org/abs/2104.08686). It should have all the information you need to understand the model and to make a Bachelier volatility surface (as well as much more).

## 7.2 - Bonus extensions
There are also some other extensions we think may be interesting to try out in your own time, but would take too much time to properly address in the session. If you do any of these we'd greatly appreciate updates on how they went:
- Modelling Volatility surfaces:
    - Implementing the SVI model discussed previously. The original SVI model paper is [Arbitrage-free SVI volatility surfaces](https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2033323). There's also a very impressive Masters Thesis that explains the SVI model and some extensions to it: [The SVI implied volatility model and its calibration](https://kth.diva-portal.org/smash/get/diva2:744907/FULLTEXT02.pdf). Links to papers on some extensions (SSVI, eSSVI) can be found in the references. 
    - Using VAEs to estimate / interpolate over the missing regions of the volatility surface. A company that makes valuation and risk management tools, Riskfuel Analytics, uses (or once used) variational autoencoders to quickly determine volatility surfaces for different assets. More details can be found in this paper: [Variational Autoencoders: A Hands-Off Approach to Volatility](https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2033323)
    - Some other approaches try to model the probability density of the time T price of the underlying. A method from this paper: [Option-based Equity Risk Premiums](https://arxiv.org/pdf/1910.14522) suggests the use of Gaussian Mixture Models for the underlying, fitting these models so the resulting density matches the implied volatilities observed. One can then easily compute the rest of the volatility surface using the pdf of the underlying.
    - [Kriging the Local Volatility Surface](https://www.bayes.city.ac.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0010/640477/SIFIN_Option_Pricing.pdf) describes a Kriging based volatility surface interpolation method. This method allows for no-arbitrage constraints and can be evaluated relatively quickly.
    - For interest, this paper has a comparison of many different volatility surface construction methods' performance on a large dataset of options prices: [Implied volatility surfaces: a comprehensive analysis using half a billion option prices](https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s11147-023-09195-5)
- Even faster IV computations:
    - This paper by Peter Jaeckel is slightly outdated, but has a much faster method of computing the implied volatility than ours: [By Implication](http://www.jaeckel.org/ByImplication.pdf)
    - This paper has a more modern (and faster) method of computing the implied volatility: [Let's be rational](http://www.jaeckel.org/LetsBeRational.pdf)
- Trading strategies:
    - Another extension is to implement the volatility term structure trading strategy mentioned above. A paper that implements this can be found here: [Equity Volatility Term Structures and the Cross-Section of Option Returns](https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=1944298)
    - You could also look into a strategy which makes use of the full volatility surface instead of only the volatility term structure for a fixed strike or the volatility skew for a single maturity date. An example is this paper: [Risk-Neutral Skewness and Stock Outperformance](https://wp.lancs.ac.uk/fofi2018/files/2018/03/FoFI-2017-0020-Konstantinos-Gkionis.pdf) which uses Risk-Neutral Skewness, a measure computed from implied volatilities to generate returns.

We can see it stores the strike price, days to expiration, implied volatility, yfinance computed implied volatility and the price. This is not enough information to perform all the filtering we may want to do. For instance, to filter out prices that were more than 5 days old and no longer accurate we would need to know when that price was seen (if it was not computed based on the current bid and ask price). We will make a new function, get_filterable_surface_data, that returns the valid_options data frame with the following columns included:
- days_since_trade - This is 0 if the midpoint of the current bid and ask price was used, and the number of days since the trade took place if the most recent trade was used (Reminder: this is done when the current bid and ask price are 0 according to yfinance's inputs)
- spread - when the bid - ask price is used, we store the size of the spread. We'll use this to filter by ignoring options who's prices had a particularly large spread relative to the typical spread sizes seen.
- call / put - to determine if an option is out of the money or in the money we need to know if it's a call or a put option, so this must be saved. 

For the days since trade, we need to compute this as the yfinance library returns the last traded date. We will now discuss this aspect.

Now we combine all of this into the new function


```python
def get_filterable_surface_data(ticker, tol_height = 0.001, tol_width = 0.001):
    ticker_options_df = get_options_data(ticker)
    midpoint = 0.5 * (ticker_options_df["bid"] + ticker_options_df["ask"])
    
    # In some cases, yfinance has no data for the bid and ask prices. It often returns 0s here instead of saying that it doesn't have any data.
    # To avoid this, we'll set the price to be the midpoint when bid and ask prices exist, and the most recent price otherwise.
    prices = [x if x != 0 else y for x,y in zip(midpoint, ticker_options_df["lastPrice"])]
    ticker_options_df["Average_price"] = prices

    yf_ticker = yf.Ticker(ticker)
    yf_ticker_data = yf_ticker.history()
    last_quoted_price = yf_ticker_data["Close"].iloc[-1] # gets the last close data.

    init_lower = 0.001
    init_upper = 100
    ticker_options_df = ticker_options_df[ticker_options_df["DTE"]!=0]
    option_prices = ticker_options_df[["Average_price"]].to_numpy()
    strikes = ticker_options_df[["strike"]].to_numpy()
    DTEs = ticker_options_df[["DTE"]].to_numpy()
    yfin_IVs = ticker_options_df[["impliedVolatility"]].to_numpy()
    calls = ticker_options_df[["call"]].to_numpy()

    IVs = [BS_brent_method(days_to_expiry/365, strike_price, last_quoted_price,risk_free, 
                       init_lower, init_upper, option_price, tol_height=tol_height, tol_width=tol_width, call= call)
                       for days_to_expiry, strike_price, option_price, call in zip(DTEs, strikes, option_prices, calls)]
    
    current_time = datetime.datetime.today().astimezone(tz = datetime.timezone.utc)
    time_since_trade = (current_time - ticker_options_df["lastTradeDate"])
    days_since_trade = np.array([x.days for x in time_since_trade])
    spread = (ticker_options_df["ask"] - ticker_options_df["bid"])
    non_zero_vec = ticker_options_df["ask"] != 0
    # If the ask is 0, clearly the bid is also 0 and we should discard it 
    # (or if the bid is non zero something has gone very wrong)
    spread = np.array([spread_i if non_zero_vec_i else np.NaN for spread_i, non_zero_vec_i in zip(spread, non_zero_vec)])

    valid_indices = [not isinstance(iv, str) for iv in IVs]
    valid_IVs = [iv for iv in IVs if not isinstance(iv,str)]
    valid_IVs = np.squeeze(np.array(valid_IVs))
    valid_strikes = np.squeeze(strikes[valid_indices])
    valid_DTEs = np.squeeze(DTEs[valid_indices])
    valid_yfin_IVs = np.squeeze(yfin_IVs[valid_indices])
    valid_prices = np.squeeze(option_prices[valid_indices])
    valid_calls = np.squeeze(calls[valid_indices])

    valid_spread = spread[valid_indices]
    valid_days_since_trade = days_since_trade[valid_indices]

    valid_options = pd.DataFrame({"strike":valid_strikes,
                              "DTE":valid_DTEs,
                              "IV":valid_IVs, 
                              "yfin_IV":valid_yfin_IVs, 
                              "price": valid_prices,
                              "call":valid_calls,
                              "days_since_trade": valid_days_since_trade,
                              "spread": valid_spread})
    return(valid_options)
```

### 7.3.1 - Filtering based on recency
Our method defaults to using the most recent price whenever the bid and ask prices are 0 (which is yfinance's way of saying they're invalid). If they are 0, then in the previous section we would've set the spread price to be np.NaN. We want to filter out options with days_since_trade greater than 5, and can do so using the following code


```python
# Filtering out options where the last traded date is more than 5 days ago and the midpoint price is invalid.
time_filtered_options_df = valid_options[(valid_options["days_since_trade"] < 5) | ~np.isnan(valid_options["spread"])]
time_filtered_options_df.shape
```

It's possible several options fall into this criteria, but for many stocks this will only remove only a single option, or none at all. 

### 7.3.2 - Filtering in/out of the money options
As discussed previously, there are several benefits to our accuracy that can be achieved by filtering out the in the money options. We'll allow for at the money strikes by including any option within $10 of the current price. 

- For a put option, it is out of the money (by this definition) if: strike_price < (current_price+10).

- For a call option, it is out of the money (by this definition) if: strike_price > (current_price-10).

### 7.3.3 - Filtering based on spread
As previously discussed, we also need to filter out options prices where the midpoint method was used and the spread is quite large. We do this after removing the ITM options because those generally have higher values (and so higher spreads) than OTM options. We will filter spreads more than 2.5 standard deviations from the mean (This decision is quite arbitrary, and other outlier detection methods could also be used).

### 7.3.4 - Comparing the volatility surfaces
We now check this by comparing them. We will
- Make a function that takes in a dataframe of the form of valid_options and produces a rainbow coloured volatility surface plot with grid lines
- Run this for the valid_options for Apple, and for the filtered version of this
- Plot the results and compare them.


```python
def plot_vol_surface(plotted_options, interp_type = "linear", use_yf = False, plot_title = ""):
    # Setting up grids
    strike_vec = np.linspace(min(plotted_options["strike"]), max(plotted_options["strike"]))
    DTE_vec = np.linspace(min(plotted_options["DTE"]), max(plotted_options["DTE"]))
    X,Y = np.meshgrid(strike_vec,DTE_vec) # Standard function that forms a 2D grid from the linspaces we've just created
    if use_yf:
        IVs = plotted_options["yfin_IV"]
    else:
        IVs = plotted_options["IV"]
    
    # Defining and doing the cubic spline interpolation step
    if interp_type == "linear":
        interpolator = LinearNDInterpolator(list(zip(plotted_options["strike"],plotted_options["DTE"])), IVs)
    else:
        interpolator = CloughTocher2DInterpolator(list(zip(plotted_options["strike"],plotted_options["DTE"])), IVs)
    IV_vals = interpolator(X,Y)

    # Creating the standard figure:
    fig = go.Figure(data = [go.Surface(x=strike_vec, y=DTE_vec, z=IV_vals, colorscale = "Jet", surfacecolor=IV_vals)])
    fig.update_layout(title = plot_title, autosize = False,
                    width = 600, height= 600, 
                    margin = dict(l=50, r=50, t=90, b=50))
    fig.update_scenes(zaxis_title_text = "Implied Volatility",
                      xaxis_title_text = "Strike",
                      yaxis_title_text = "Days to expiry")

    # Creating a grid in an order that leads to lines parallel to the DTE axis instead of parallel to the strike axis:
    X_rev, Y_rev =np.meshgrid(DTE_vec, strike_vec)
    # Setting the parameters of the lines on our grid:
    line_marker = dict(color="black",width=2)

    # Adding grid lines in one direction:
    for x,y,z in zip(X,Y,IV_vals):
        fig.add_trace(go.Scatter3d(x=x,y=y,z=z, mode="lines",line=line_marker, showlegend=False))

    # Adding grid lines in the other direction:
    for x,y,z in zip(X_rev, Y_rev, IV_vals.T):
        fig.add_trace(go.Scatter3d(x=y,y=x,z=z, mode="lines",line=line_marker, showlegend=False))

    fig.show()
```

## 7.4 - Approximating the normal CDF
We'll now consider other approximations of the normal CDF. We'll try out some of the methods considered in this paper: [Approximating the cumulative distribution function of the normal distribution](http://jsr.isrt.ac.bd/wp-content/uploads/41n1_5.pdf). This paper compares many methods and then combines them to produce an overall best estimate. We will:
- Implement the 3 the methods from the paper that performed well and were included in their final method. 
- Plot the CDFs of these three methods.
- Use a highly accurate numerical integration method to compute a more accurate value for the CDF.
- Compare our 3 new methods, as well as the SciPy one we're currently using, in terms of their errors compared to the more accurate values
- Compare the time taken to compute our 3 new methods with the SciPy one we're currently using.
- If the method suggested by the paper performs well, we'll then implement it and use it instead of the SciPy method.


### 7.4.1 - Approximation formulae from the paper
In the paper, they determine that the most accurate methods are:
- Byrc - 2001: https://www.academia.edu/23541563/A_uniform_approximation_to_the_right_normal_tail_integral
- Zelen and Severo - 1964: https://personal.math.ubc.ca/~cbm/aands/abramowitz_and_stegun.pdf
- Bagby - 1995: https://www.jstor.org/stable/2974857

We now implement each of these.


```python
# Byrc - 2001, formula B.
def Phi_Byrc(x):
    numerator = x**2 + 5.575192695 * x + 12.77436324
    denominator = np.sqrt(2* np.pi )*x**3 + 14.38718147*x**2 + 31.53531977*x + 25.548726
    fraction = numerator / denominator
    return 1 - fraction * np.exp(-0.5*x**2)
```


```python
# Zelen and Severo - 1964,
def Phi_Zelen(x):
    t = 1/(1 + 0.33267*x)
    term_1 = t*(0.4361836 - 0.1201676*t**1 + 0.9372980*t**2)
    term_2 = 1/np.sqrt(2*np.pi) * np.exp(-0.5*x**2)
    result = 1 - term_1 * term_2
    return result
```


```python
# Bagby - 1995,
def Phi_Bagby(x):
    x_sqr = x**2
    inner_term = 7*np.exp(-0.5*x_sqr)+16 * np.exp(-(2-np.sqrt(2))*x_sqr) + (7 + np.pi * x_sqr/4)*np.exp(-x_sqr)
    middle_term = 1 - 1/30 * inner_term
    outer_term = 0.5 + 0.5 * np.sqrt(middle_term)
    return outer_term
```


```python
# Plotting our approximations:
x = np.linspace(0,3)
y_Byrc = Phi_Byrc(x)
y_Zelen = Phi_Zelen(x)
y_Bagby = Phi_Bagby(x)
# plot_df = pd.DataFrame({"x":x, "Byrc":y_Byrc, "Zelen":y_Zelen,"Bagby":y_Bagby})

fig.add_trace(go.Scatter(x=x, y=y_Byrc, mode="lines",name="Byrc"))
fig.add_trace(go.Scatter(x=x, y=y_Zelen, mode="lines",name="Zelen"))
fig.add_trace(go.Scatter(x=x, y=y_Bagby, mode="lines",name="Bagby"))
fig.show()
```

### 7.4.2 - True CDF values
To compute the errors, we need some true / highly accurate values for the normal CDF. We will use an integration method to perform this. In the paper, they use a Monte-Carlo based method to produce highly accurate (but slow to compute) estimates of the normal CDF. We'll instead use mpmath, a python library that allows for high precision computations. We'll use the quad function, which computes numerical approximations of integrals. 


```python
import mpmath
mpmath.mp.dps = 50 # decimal digits of precision

def norm_pdf(x):
    x = mpmath.mpf(x)
    return mpmath.sqrt(1/(2*mpmath.pi)) * mpmath.exp(-x**2/2)


# def cdf(x,k): 
#     x,k = mpmath.mpf(x), mpmath.mpf(k) 
#     return mpmath.gammainc(k/2, 0, x/2, regularized=True)

def cdf_via_quad(s_list):
    return [float(0.5 + mpmath.quad(lambda x: norm_pdf(x), [0, s])) for s in s_list]

# evaluating this method at some chosen points
points = [0.1,0.3,0.5,1, 1.6, 2.3, 2.8]
mpmath_result = np.array(cdf_via_quad(points))
mpmath_result

### 7.4.3 - Plotting the error
Next, we plot the errors of our 3 methods and the SciPy implementation against the mpmath quadrature implementation.


```python
x = np.linspace(0,3,250)
mpmath_vals = np.array(cdf_via_quad(x))
```


```python
Byrc_error = Phi_Byrc(x) - mpmath_vals
Bagby_error = Phi_Bagby(x) - mpmath_vals
Zelen_error= Phi_Zelen(x) - mpmath_vals
SciPy_error = Phi(x) - mpmath_vals
```


```python
fig = go.Figure()
fig.add_trace(go.Scatter(x=x, y=Byrc_error , mode="lines",name="Byrc"))
fig.add_trace(go.Scatter(x=x, y=Bagby_error, mode="lines",name="Bagby"))
fig.add_trace(go.Scatter(x=x, y=Zelen_error, mode="lines",name="Zelen"))
fig.add_trace(go.Scatter(x=x, y=SciPy_error, mode="lines", name="SciPy"))
fig.update_layout(title = "Errors to true values", autosize = False,
                    width = 1100, height= 600)
fig.show()
```

From this plot, we can see that all of the methods had an error below $30\times 10^{-6}$ on the relevant interval. SciPy's implementation had an error smaller than machine precision compared to the mpmath procedure, so it's definitely more accurate than the other numerical methods. 

Next, we compare their runtimes (because if the SciPy method takes 100 times longer to compute than the others it may be better to use a less accurate but faster method). 


```python
import timeit
def Phi_Byrc_time_test():
    Phi_Byrc(x)
def Phi_Bagby_time_test():
    Phi_Bagby(x)
def Phi_Zelen_time_test():
    Phi_Zelen(x)
def Phi_SciPy_time_test():
    Phi(x)
```


```python
# Takes about a minute to run as we run each function many times.
Byrc_time = min(timeit.Timer(Phi_Byrc_time_test).repeat(repeat=50000, number=1))
Bagby_time = min(timeit.Timer(Phi_Bagby_time_test).repeat(repeat=50000, number=1))
Zelen_time = min(timeit.Timer(Phi_Zelen_time_test).repeat(repeat=50000, number=1))
SciPy_time = min(timeit.Timer(Phi_SciPy_time_test).repeat(repeat=50000, number=1))
```


```python
fig = go.Figure()
fig.add_trace(go.Bar(
    x = ["Byrc Time", "Bagby Time","Zelen Time","SciPy Time"],
    y = [Byrc_time,Bagby_time, Zelen_time, SciPy_time],
    name = "Time taken to compute normal CDF for 250 points",
    marker = dict(color = "#67D5D0")
))
fig.update_layout(title = "Time taken to compute normal CDF for 250 points", autosize = False,
                    width = 1100, height= 600)
fig.show()

However, we used Scipy's `scipy.stats.norm.cdf` for `Phi`. An alternative is to use `scipy.special.ndtr`. This is the function `norm.cdf` uses under the hood, but using it directly improves performance as we no longer perform some of the checks that `norm.cdf` uses. Therefore, it makes sense to stick with the SciPy implementation instead of the one from the paper.

## 7.5 - Hybrid Newton method
Just before we worked through Brent's method for finding a root of a function, we discussed a hybrid Newton-Raphson and Bisection method. This is less widely applicable than Brent's method as it requires a fast to compute derivative for our function. In the Black-Scholes context, the derivative is actually easier to compute than the pricing function itself as it doesn't include the normal distribution CDF. Therefore, it makes some sense to try to it out and see if we can speed up the convergence of our method (therefore speeding up our computation of implied volatility prices). We'll use a similar approach to the Brent's method code.


```python
def hybrid_newton_w_counter(FUN, deriv_FUN, a, b, target_value, tol_height, tol_width, delta = 0.001, return_counter = False):
    def f(x):
        return FUN(x) - target_value

    def deriv_f(x): 
        return deriv_FUN(x) # Target value is a constant, so not included in derivative.
    # Save values to avoid calling f multiple times, speeding up computation.
    f_a = f(a)
    f_b = f(b)
    if f_a*f_b >= 0:
        return f"Error: No change of sign between {a} and {b}, can't perform method."
    if abs(f_a) < abs(f_b):
        # swapping a and b, f_a and f_b
        a,b = swap(a,b)
        f_a, f_b = swap(f_a, f_b)
    b_prev = a
    b_2_prev = 0
    bisect_flag = True
    s = np.array([b])
    counter = 0
    while abs(f_b) > tol_height and abs(b-a) > tol_width:
        counter+=1
        s = newton_raphson(f, deriv_f, init_point = b, target_value = target_value, tol = 0, max_iterations=1)[0]
        if conditions(s,a,b,b_prev, b_2_prev, bisect_flag, delta):
            s = 0.5*(a+b)
            bisect_flag = True
        else:
            bisect_flag = False
        f_s = f(s)

        # Saving the old values:
        b_2_prev = b_prev
        b_prev = b

        # Determine which interval root is now in:
        if f_a * f_s < 0:
            b = s
            f_b = f_s
        else:
            a = s
            f_a = f_s
        if abs(f_a) < abs(f_b):
            a,b = swap(a,b)
            f_a,f_b = swap(f_a, f_b)
    if return_counter:
        return s,counter
    else:
        return s
    
```

Some notes:
- Even when Hybrid NR uses fewer iterations, it still takes far longer to converge than Brent's method. This is likely because our current implementation of Hybrid NR doesn't save previous values for f_a and f_b, instead computing them multiple times.
- Not entirely sure why Hybrid NR takes more iterations to converge, but it appears that newton's method performs (comparatively) worse when the gradient is steeper near the root. 
- I don't believe there are any performance guarantees for the Hybrid Newton method, so it may be that despite Newton Raphson having a higher order of convergence than inverse quadratic interpolation, the way it's combined with bisection reduces it.
- It's also possible that the optimal `conditions` function is different for Hybrid Newton than for Brent, and that this needs modifications to improve it's performance.

## 7.6 - Using the Bachelier model



### 7.6.1 - Introduction to the Bachelier Model

The Bachelier model (sometimes called the "normal" model in comparison to the log-normality of the Black-Scholes model) is another model one can price optons under. The most widely known application of the Bachelier model was when in April 2020, the demand for oil dropped sharply and futures contracts' prices' became negative. It has had other uses, such as:
- In fixed income markets where it appears that the changes in interest rate are not (at least not strongly) proportional to the size of the current interest rate (which is a key assumption of the Black-Scholes model).
- In pricing [spread options](https://www.investopedia.com/terms/s/spreadoption.asp) , which payout the difference between two stock's prices at some point in the future, because these are often negative.
- In inflation modelling, as some evidence suggests [inflation is normal](https://www.risk.net/derivatives/inflation-derivatives/1500273/inflation-normal) instead of log-normal.



### 7.6.2 - Bachelier options prices

We'll now discuss Bachelier options prices and implied volatilities, using the paper: [A Black-Scholes user's guide to the Bachelier model](https://arxiv.org/abs/2104.08686) as a reference throughout. The price of a call option with strike $K$, time to expiration $T$, time 0 forward price $F_0$ and volatility $\sigma$ in the Bachelier model is:

$$C_N(\sigma) = (F_0 - K) \Phi(d(\sigma)) + \sigma \sqrt{T} \Phi'(d(\sigma))  \text{ where } d(\sigma) = \frac{F_0 - K}{\sigma \sqrt{T}}$$

The forward price is generally relevant to commodities, currencies and other assets with forward contracts. It is usually based on the spot price, and also varies with carrying costs, storage costs and foregone interest (the difference between interest that would've been paid if it was in cash the whole time and what was actually paid). In this context, the forward price $F_0 = S_0 e^{(q-r)T}$ where $r$ is the (continuously compounded) interest rate and $q$ is the convenience yield of the asset (convenience yeild is a term not found in equities. Owners of a commodity can have several advantages compared to owners of a future for that same commodity. If the price suddenly spikes, they can sell some off and take advantage of the short term shock. If they are a manufacturer, owning the commodity allows them to continue production. For this reason we have both a positive and negative term involved in the forward - current price relationship). 

The Put option price is:

$$P_N(\sigma) = (K- F_0) \Phi(-d(\sigma)) + \sigma \sqrt{T} \Phi'(d(\sigma))  \text{ where } d(\sigma) = \frac{F_0 - K}{\sigma \sqrt{T}}$$

#### At the money approximation:
Much like for the Black-Scholes model, there is an analytic way to express the implied volatility in the Bachelier model in the ATM case. In this case however it is exact. For at the money options (where $K=F_0$) we get, by substituting this into our expression for the call price, the following:

$$C_N(\sigma) = \sigma \sqrt{\frac{T}{2\pi}}$$

Now rearranging gives us:

$$\sigma = C_N(\sigma)\sqrt{\frac{2\pi}{T}}$$

So we have an easy way to (exactly) determine the volatility given a partcular price for at the money options. We will now look at other options.


### 7.6.3 - Implied Volatilities in the Bachelier model

For this section, we'll use the work of this paper [Numerical Approximation of the Implied Volatility Under Arithmetic Brownian Motion](https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/13504860802583436). They derive a very accurate and fast numerical approximation of the IV in the Bachelier model. We'll briefly cover this derivation.

Firstly, we note that (for the same strike price) the Put-Call parity relation in the Bachelier model is exactly the same as for the black scholes price, $C-P = K - S_T$. Now given a put price or call price (and the strike and current price of the stock, which are known publicly) we can compute the call or put price for that volatility respectively. We can also compute $P+C$, the sum of the put and call prices. We will now look at the Bachelier price of $P+C$:

$$P+C = (F_0 - K) \Phi(d(\sigma)) + \sigma \sqrt{T} \Phi'(d(\sigma)) + (K- F_0) \Phi(-d(\sigma)) + \sigma \sqrt{T} \Phi'(d(\sigma)) $$

$$P+C= (F_0 - K)(\Phi(d(\sigma)) - \Phi(-d(\sigma))) + 2\sigma \sqrt{T} \Phi'(d(\sigma)) = (F_0 - K)(2\Phi(d(\sigma)) - 1) + 2\sigma \sqrt{T} \Phi'(d(\sigma))$$

rearranging this, we get:

$$\frac{F_0-K}{P+C} = \frac{1}{(2\Phi(d(\sigma)) - 1) + 2 \frac{\sigma \sqrt{T}}{F_0-K}\Phi'(d(\sigma))} = \frac{1}{(2\Phi(d(\sigma)) - 1) + 2 \frac{1}{d}\Phi'(d(\sigma))} = \frac{d(\sigma)}{d(\sigma)(2\Phi(d(\sigma)) - 1) + 2\Phi'(d(\sigma))}$$

where we use the definition of $d$. Next we define 
$$v(\sigma)= \frac{d(\sigma)}{d(\sigma)(2\Phi(d(\sigma)) - 1) + 2\Phi'(d(\sigma))}$$

Note a key properties of $v$, that $|v|<1$. To see this, consider $P+C$ as the volatility tends to 0. Clearly $P+C$ = |F_0 - K|, as the time $T$ stock price tends to $F_0$, and the payout from a put and a call option added together is $(S_T-K)^+ + (K-S_T)^+$. Now for non-zero volatilities, the put price and call price both increase giving us that $|v| =|\frac{F_0-K}{P+C}| < 1$.

The paper then goes on to perform some transformations to improve the behaviour of their final approximation scheme which we will now detail. We can treat $v = v(d)$ as a function of only $d$, temporarily dropping the dependence on $\sigma$. Doing so, one could invert $v(d)$ to determine $d$ in terms of $\frac{F_0-K}{P+C}$ (which can be easily computed as mentioned at the start of this section). There is some subtlety around the ATM case (a 0/0 emerges) which leads to needing different approaches for very close to the money options and for those further from the money. To avoid this, the paper views all options as a (sometimes large) perturbation of the ATM case. Note when we're at the money (i.e. $F_0 = K$), we have $d=0$ and so:

$$P+C = (0)\times(2\Phi(0) - 1) + 2\sigma \sqrt{T} \Phi'(0) =2\sigma \sqrt{T} \times \frac{1}{\sqrt{2 \pi}} e^{-0^2/2}$$

and simplifying we get:

$$P+C = \sigma\sqrt{\frac{2T}{\pi}}$$

To perturb this, we introduce a parameter $h = \sqrt{\frac{2}{\pi}}\frac{v}{d}$. By the definition of $d$, and the fact that $v = \frac{F_0-K}{P+C}$ we get $h = \sqrt{\frac{2}{\pi}} \frac{F_0-K}{P+C}\frac{\sigma \sqrt{T}}{F_0-K}$, and rearranging this gives:

$$(P+C)h = \sqrt{\frac{2T}{\pi}}\sigma$$

and we can then rearrange for $\sigma$, the implied volatility, is:

$$\sigma = \sqrt{\frac{\pi}{2T}}(P+C)h$$

Note that this perturbation $h$ is, by definition, bounded between 0 and 1. This is because the maximum value of:

$$d/v(d) = d(2\Phi(d) - 1) + 2\Phi'(d)$$

in terms of $d$ is at $d=0$, where it takes the value $\sqrt{\pi/2}$ (can show this with some calculus). The minimum value for $d>0$ is clearly 0. Hence $h(d)\in [0,1]$ (for $d>0$).


The paper then transforms $v$ to $\eta = \frac{v}{\text{tanh}^{-1}(v)}$ because the properties of $h$ considered as a function of $\eta$ are much nicer than $h(v)$. Lastly, they use Rational Chebyshev approximation (Can be found in Numerical Recipes in C, page 204) to create a polynomial capable of approximating $h(\eta)/\eta$ with high accuracy. This process is somewhat involved and an interested reader should look at Numerical Recipes in C, page 204 and it's references for further details.

They find that a good approximation of $h(\eta)$ is given by:

$$h(\eta) = \sqrt{\eta}\times \frac{\sum_{k=0}^7 a_k \eta^k}{\sum_{k=0}^9 b_k \eta^k}$$ 

where:

| Term   | Value|
| -------- | ------- |
| $a_0$ | $3.994961687345134 \times 10^{-1}$|
| $a_1$ | $2.100960795068497 \times 10^{1}$ |
| $a_2$ | $4.980340217855084 \times 10^{1}$|
| $a_3$ | $5.988761102690991 \times 10^{2}$|
| $a_4$ | $1.848489695437094 \times 10^{3}$|
| $a_5$ | $6.106322407867059 \times 10^{3}$|
| $a_6$ | $2.493415285349361 \times 10^{4}$|
| $a_7$ | $1.266458051348246 \times 10^{4}$|

and:

| Term   | Value|
| -------- | ------- |
| $b_1$ | $4.990534153589422 \times 10^{1}$|
| $b_2$ | $3.093573936743112 \times 10^{1}$|
| $b_3$ | $1.495105008310999 \times 10^{3}$|
| $b_4$ | $1.323614537899738 \times 10^{3}$|
| $b_5$ | $1.598919697679745 \times 10^{4}$|
| $b_6$ | $2.392008891720782 \times 10^{4}$|
| $b_7$ | $3.608817108375034 \times 10^{3}$|
| $b_8$ | $-2.067719486400926 \times 10^{2}$|
| $b_9$ | $1.174240599306013 \times 10^{1}$|

In summary, to determine the bachelier implied volatility of an option with call price $C$ (alternatively put price $P$) we:
- Use put-call parity to determine $P$ (alternatively $C$)
- Add these to get $P+C$
- Use the current stock price to determine $F_0$
- Set $v = |F_0 - K| / (P+C)$
- Let $\eta = \frac{v}{\text{tanh}^{-1}(v)}$
- Compute $h(\eta)$ using $h(\eta) = \sqrt{\eta}\times \frac{\sum_{k=0}^7 a_k \eta^k}{\sum_{k=0}^9 b_k \eta^k}$
- Substitute our result for $h(\eta)$ into $\sigma = \sqrt{\frac{\pi}{2T}}(P+C)h(\eta)$

### 7.6.4 - Code implementation
Now we put all of this into code to check it's correct and to determine how fast it is compared to a naive root finding approach. Firstly, we'll code the Bachelier Put and Call prices


```python
def bachelier_call_price(vol, time_to_expiry, strike_price, current_price, risk_free, convenience_yield = 0):
    forward_price = current_price * np.exp((risk_free - convenience_yield)*time_to_expiry)
    intrinsic_value = forward_price - strike_price
    d = intrinsic_value / (vol * np.sqrt(time_to_expiry))
    term_1 = intrinsic_value * Phi(d) 
    term_2 = vol * np.sqrt(time_to_expiry) * deriv_Phi(d)
    undiscounted_price = term_1 + term_2
    discounted_price = undiscounted_price * np.exp((convenience_yield-risk_free)*time_to_expiry)
    return discounted_price

def bachelier_put_price(vol, time_to_expiry, strike_price, current_price, risk_free, convenience_yield = 0):
    forward_price = current_price * np.exp((risk_free - convenience_yield)*time_to_expiry)
    intrinsic_value = strike_price - forward_price
    d = -1 *intrinsic_value / (vol * np.sqrt(time_to_expiry))
    term_1 = intrinsic_value * Phi(-d)
    term_2 = vol * np.sqrt(time_to_expiry) * deriv_Phi(-d)
    undiscounted_price = term_1 + term_2
    discounted_price = undiscounted_price * np.exp((convenience_yield-risk_free)*time_to_expiry)
    return discounted_price
```


```python
def get_straddle_price(time_to_expiry, strike_price, current_price, risk_free, options_price, 
                        is_call, convenience_yield = 0, discounted = False):
    # Uses put-call parity to compute the straddle price.
    forward_strike = strike_price * np.exp((convenience_yield-risk_free)*time_to_expiry)
    if not discounted:
        disc_options_price = options_price * np.exp((convenience_yield-risk_free)*time_to_expiry)
    else:
        disc_options_price = options_price
    if is_call:
        disc_call_price = disc_options_price
        disc_put_price = disc_call_price + forward_strike - current_price
    else:
        disc_put_price = disc_options_price
        disc_call_price = disc_put_price + current_price - forward_strike
    put_price = disc_put_price * np.exp((risk_free - convenience_yield)*time_to_expiry)
    call_price = disc_call_price * np.exp((risk_free - convenience_yield)*time_to_expiry)
    return (call_price + put_price)

def get_abs_intrinsic_value(time_to_expiry, strike_price, current_price, risk_free, convenience_yield = 0):
    forward_price = current_price * np.exp((risk_free - convenience_yield)*time_to_expiry)
    intrinsic_value = forward_price - strike_price
    return(np.abs(intrinsic_value))

def get_v(time_to_expiry, strike_price, current_price, risk_free, options_price, is_call, convenience_yield = 0, discounted = True):
    numerator = get_abs_intrinsic_value(time_to_expiry, strike_price, current_price, risk_free, convenience_yield = convenience_yield)
    denominator = get_straddle_price(time_to_expiry, strike_price, current_price, risk_free, 
                                     options_price, is_call, convenience_yield = convenience_yield, discounted = discounted)
    v = numerator / denominator
    return(v)

def eta_from_v(v):
    numerator = v
    denominator = np.arctanh(v)
    eta = numerator/denominator
    if not np.isscalar(eta):
        eta = eta[0]
    return(eta)

def h_from_eta(eta):
    a = np.array([3.994961687345134e-1, 2.100960795068497e1, 4.980340217855084e1, 5.988761102690991e2, 1.848489695437094e3, 
                  6.106322407867059e3, 2.493415285349361e4, 1.266458051348246e4])
    b = np.array([1,4.990534153589422e1, 3.093573936743112e1, 1.495105008310999e3, 1.323614537899738e3, 1.598919697679745e4,
                  2.392008891720782e4, 3.608817108375034e3, -2.067719486400926e2, 1.174240599306013e1])
    len_a = len(a)
    len_b = len(b)
    eta_powers_a = np.geomspace(1, eta**(len_a-1), num=len_a)
    eta_powers_b = np.geomspace(1,eta**(len_b-1), num=len_b)
    numerator = sum(np.multiply(eta_powers_a,a))
    denominator = sum(eta_powers_b * b)
    h = numerator / denominator
    return( np.sqrt(eta) * h)

def get_bachelier_IV(time_to_expiry, strike_price, current_price, risk_free, options_price, is_call, discounted = True, convenience_yield = 0):
    # if not discounted:
    #     options_price = options_price * np.exp((convenience_yield-risk_free)*time_to_expiry)
    v = get_v(time_to_expiry, strike_price, current_price, risk_free, 
              options_price, is_call, convenience_yield = convenience_yield, discounted = discounted)
    eta = eta_from_v(v)
    
    h = h_from_eta(eta)
    straddle_price = get_straddle_price(time_to_expiry, strike_price, current_price, risk_free, 
                                        options_price, is_call, convenience_yield=convenience_yield, discounted = True)
    term_1 = np.sqrt(np.pi/(2 * time_to_expiry))
    term_2 = straddle_price * h
    IV = term_1 * term_2
    return(IV)
```

# Bachelier version of the BS_brent_method function:

def bachelier_brent_method(time_to_expiry, strike_price, current_price, risk_free, a,b,target_value, tol_height, tol_width, is_call):
    if is_call:
        def FUN(x):
            return bachelier_call_price(x, time_to_expiry, strike_price, current_price, risk_free)
    else:
        def FUN(x):
            return bachelier_put_price(x, time_to_expiry, strike_price, current_price, risk_free)
    return brent_method(FUN, a,b,target_value, tol_height,tol_width)

We can see that the analytic method is around 10x faster than Brent's method with these tolerances. It is also many times more accurate so it is better in every way by a significant margin.

### 7.6.5 - Bachelier volatility surfaces
Lastly, we explore volatility surfaces using Bachelier IVs instead of Black-Scholes IVs. We're going to do this on equities data, just to see what happens (Bachelier IVs should only really be used for commodities and other assets with near 0 / negative values). 

We can use very similar functions to what we do above, we just need to tweak them to run get_bachelier_IV instead of the BS_brent_method function they currently use. We'll do this by updating the get_filterable_surface_data function, so we can also apply filtering. This gives:


```python
def get_filterable_surface_data(ticker, tol_height = 0.001, tol_width = 0.001, IV_type = "BS"):
    ticker_options_df = get_options_data(ticker)
    midpoint = 0.5 * (ticker_options_df["bid"] + ticker_options_df["ask"])
    
    # In some cases, yfinance has no data for the bid and ask prices. It often returns 0s here instead of saying that it doesn't have any data.
    # To avoid this, we'll set the price to be the midpoint when bid and ask prices exist, and the most recent price otherwise.
    prices = [x if x != 0 else y for x,y in zip(midpoint, ticker_options_df["lastPrice"])]
    ticker_options_df["Average_price"] = prices

    yf_ticker = yf.Ticker(ticker)
    yf_ticker_data = yf_ticker.history()
    last_quoted_price = yf_ticker_data["Close"].iloc[-1] # gets the last close data.

    init_lower = 0.001
    init_upper = 100
    ticker_options_df = ticker_options_df[ticker_options_df["DTE"]!=0]
    option_prices = ticker_options_df[["Average_price"]].to_numpy()
    strikes = ticker_options_df[["strike"]].to_numpy()
    DTEs = ticker_options_df[["DTE"]].to_numpy()
    yfin_IVs = ticker_options_df[["impliedVolatility"]].to_numpy()
    calls = ticker_options_df[["call"]].to_numpy()
    if IV_type == "BS":
        IVs = [BS_brent_method(days_to_expiry/365, strike_price, last_quoted_price,risk_free, 
                               init_lower, init_upper, option_price, tol_height=tol_height, tol_width=tol_width, call= call)
                               for days_to_expiry, strike_price, option_price, call in zip(DTEs, strikes, option_prices, calls)]
    else:
        IVs = [get_bachelier_IV(days_to_expiry/365, strike_price, last_quoted_price,risk_free, 
                               option_price, call, discounted = True)
                               for days_to_expiry, strike_price, option_price, call in zip(DTEs, strikes, option_prices, calls)]
    current_time = datetime.datetime.today().astimezone(tz = datetime.timezone.utc)
    time_since_trade = (current_time - ticker_options_df["lastTradeDate"])
    days_since_trade = np.array([x.days for x in time_since_trade])
    spread = (ticker_options_df["ask"] - ticker_options_df["bid"])
    non_zero_vec = ticker_options_df["ask"] != 0
    # If the ask is 0, clearly the bid is also 0 and we should discard it 
    # (or if the bid is non zero something has gone very wrong)
    spread = np.array([spread_i if non_zero_vec_i else np.NaN for spread_i, non_zero_vec_i in zip(spread, non_zero_vec)])

    valid_indices = [not isinstance(iv, str) for iv in IVs]
    valid_IVs = [iv for iv in IVs if not isinstance(iv,str)]
    valid_IVs = np.squeeze(np.array(valid_IVs))
    valid_strikes = np.squeeze(strikes[valid_indices])
    valid_DTEs = np.squeeze(DTEs[valid_indices])
    valid_yfin_IVs = np.squeeze(yfin_IVs[valid_indices])
    valid_prices = np.squeeze(option_prices[valid_indices])
    valid_calls = np.squeeze(calls[valid_indices])

    valid_spread = spread[valid_indices]
    valid_days_since_trade = days_since_trade[valid_indices]

    valid_options = pd.DataFrame({"strike":valid_strikes,
                              "DTE":valid_DTEs,
                              "IV":valid_IVs, 
                              "yfin_IV":valid_yfin_IVs, 
                              "price": valid_prices,
                              "call":valid_calls,
                              "days_since_trade": valid_days_since_trade,
                              "spread": valid_spread})
    return(valid_options)

# Also make a function that can filter our options automatically:
def filter_options(valid_options, max_days = 5, ITM_threshold = 10, sds_from_mean = 2.5):
    time_filtered_options_df = valid_options[(valid_options["days_since_trade"] < max_days) | ~np.isnan(valid_options["spread"])]

    # Getting the most recent price:
    yf_ticker = yf.Ticker(ticker)
    yf_ticker_data = yf_ticker.history()
    last_quoted_price = yf_ticker_data["Close"].iloc[-1] # gets the last close data.

    # Filtering out the ITM puts
    call_mask = (time_filtered_options_df["strike"] < last_quoted_price+ITM_threshold)&(time_filtered_options_df["call"])

    put_mask = (time_filtered_options_df["strike"] > last_quoted_price-ITM_threshold)&(np.invert(time_filtered_options_df["call"]))

    OTM_filtered_options_df = time_filtered_options_df[call_mask | put_mask]

    spreads = OTM_filtered_options_df["spread"].to_numpy()
    mean = np.mean(spreads)
    sd = np.std(spreads)
    max_allowed_spread = mean+sds_from_mean*sd

    mask = spreads < max_allowed_spread
    fully_filtered_options_df = OTM_filtered_options_df[mask]
    return fully_filtered_options_df

We can see our volatility surface looks extremely unusual. The implied volatility calculations fail for some regions as their prices aren't even possible in the Bachelier model, and there is a very steep slope on our surface where it does exist. Most of this could be expected (and the slope is a reason why the Bachelier model isn't used in equities)

# 8 - Volatility Surfaces in Algorithmic Trading Strategies
In the session, we'll go through some possible applications of the volatility surface for trading strategies. One thing to think about is the following strategy:
- In many aspects of finance we see mean reversion, particularly over longer periods
- We can compute the long term mean volatility based on historical realised volatility
- For a given option, we can then compare this to the current implied volatility:
    - If the implied volatility is much higher, we sell the option as it's overpriced relative to historical volatility, and we predict the volatility will revert to the mean.
    - If the implied volatility is much lower, we buy the option as it's underpriced relative to historical volatility, and we predict the volatility will revert to the mean.

How do you think this strategy would perform?


## 8.1 - Mean reversion of volatility
Answer: One would expect this to perform poorly in general. The implied volatilities are likely different to historic values for some reason, for instance:
- Upcoming earnings announcements
- Major market events - FOMC announcements etc.
- Results of clinical trials published soon

There are a myriad of other reasons why the prices might be higher / slower than one would typically expect, and taking the position that all of them are spurious (and so will disappear over time as volatility reverts to the mean) is questionable. 

We will now discuss an implementation of this strategy in QuantConnect in brief detail, and then we'll show a graph of it's performance to confirm our supicions. 


### 8.1.1 - QC Strategy
The strategy is based off of this paper: [Understanding Foreign Exchange Option Returns: The Information Content of Volatility](https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2009289). The basic idea is, as above, that volatility should revert to historical mean values. We get the full set of options (similar to the pandas DataFrame in yfinance).

```python
# get all contracts for current etf
contracts = self.OptionChainProvider.GetOptionContractList(symbol, self.Time)

# get current price for etf
underlying_price = self.Securities[symbol].Price
```

then we get just the strike values and filter these:

```python
strikes = [i.ID.StrikePrice for i in contracts]

...

calls, puts = self.FilterContracts(strikes, contracts, underlying_price)
```

`self.FilterContracts` is a custom function that takes inthe strikes, contracts and the underlying price and returns some filtered calls and puts based on the following:
- Determines the call strike for a straddle based on the closest strike price to the current underlying price
- Sets the put strike equal to the call strike
- Runs through each contract and checks if the time to expiry is within a pre-defined range (In our case between 20 and 60 days).
- Adds the contract to the put / call list depending on its type.

Next, we check if there is at least one call / put using the following:
```python
if len(calls) and len(puts):
```

and if so we take the first call and first put (after sorting by expiry, so the ones that expire soonest) and add them to our option contracts so we monitor them in the future. 

Next, when we have sufficiently many options in our data and we have the current price, we get the implied volatilities for each put/call pair (same strike and expiry). Then, we get the historical volatility for that option. To do this, we use a RollingWindow object that stores the value of the underlying at the same time each day. We then pass this RollingWindow object, called rolling_window_prices, into the following:

```python
prices = np.array([x for x in rolling_window_prices]) 
# Forms a numpy array from our rolling window

returns = (prices[1:] - prices[:-1]) / prices[:-1] 
# prices[:-1] is prices with the last value removed, prices[1:] is prices with the first value removed
# so (prices[1:] - prices[:-1]) is the difference between the current and previous price. We then divide 
# by prices[:-1]  to get the change as a percentage. 

return np.std(returns) * np.sqrt(252)
# Lastly we return the standard deviation multiplied by root(252), the typical number of trading days per year,
# to scale the historical volatility correctly as we're including the past year of samples.
```

Next, we compute the difference between IV and historical realised volatility, using:
```python
vol_difference[symbol] = hv - iv
```
To determine when trades happen, we go long when vol_diff is high and short when it's low (if it's high, hv > iv so we would expect more volatility than the prices would indicate, therefore we should buy the straddle which profits from higher volatility. If it's low, hv < iv and we would expect less vol => should sell the straddle).

We buy and sell in quantities that ensure we never run out of capital to make new orders and never go above our risk preferences.


### 8.1.2 - QC Strategy performance

Can see this strategy loses money significantly. More importantly, it loses it consistently over a long period of time. Furthermore, if we change vol_difference to be `iv-hv` instead of `iv-hv` we get similar performance. This can be explained by IV being a far better predictor of realised volatility that historical volatility.

## 8.2 - A Volatility Term Structure strategy
Lastly, to show some practical applications of our new knowledge, we'll discuss a trading strategy that uses volatility term structure to inform trades (and hopefully make a significant profit). The key idea is as follows:
- In other papers, the slope of the IV term structure has been linked to options returns.
- More specifically, higher slopes are positively correlated with higher returns on options straddles.
- Other papers have found this phenomenon in a range of asset classes, time periods and in both ITM and OTM cases.

The paper also discusses some other more advanced analysis they use to determine other important and interesting results about how implied volatilities behave, but we will focus on the trading strategy portion and give an overview of how a QC implementation works, before showing some results.



### 8.2.1 - QC Implementation
We can get implied volatilities using `.ImpliedVolatility` on an options object, but this only gives us the IV at a single point. To determine the slope, we need at least two points. The implementation uses only two points, a short term one and a long term one. 
- Short term contracts (options) are those with expirations between 25 and 35 days
- Long term contracts (options) are those with expirations between 50 and 360 days

#### Filtering
To get these, they use a standard list filter like this:
```python
atm_calls: List[Symbol] = [i for i in contracts if i.ID.OptionRight == OptionRight.Call and i.ID.StrikePrice == atm_strike and 
                                min_expiry <= (i.ID.Date - self.Time).days <= max_expiry]
```
and a similar method is used for the puts. In these we have another filter, `i.ID.StrikePrice == atm_strike`. Here ATM strike is defined as the closest strike to the underlying, using:
```python
atm_strike: float = min(strikes, key=lambda x: abs(x-underlying_price))
```
After the filters are completed for both the put and call, we check that there is at least one option for both and then subscribe to them to get information on them in the future. 

#### Computing the Volatility term structure slopes
To compute the slopes, we loop through the options, check if they're puts or calls, and check if they're short or long term using the following:
```python
for c in contracts:
    if c.Right == OptionRight.Call:
        if ticker in self.short_term_contracts and c.Symbol in self.short_term_contracts[ticker].contracts:
            # found short term atm call
            short_atm_call_iv = c.ImpliedVolatility
```
and similar for the other parts. Now when an IV exists for all 4 points (short and long term puts and calls) one computes the short term IV as the mean of the short term put and call IVs, and similarly for the long term one. Then, check that the underlying price is still available before adding both the underlying price and the slope to a dictionaries called `stock_prices` and `slope` respectively (the entries of these will be used in the next section for doing the trades). 

#### Trading
The strategy has some fixed parameter quantile which determines what proportion of the strategies to go long / short on (i.e. if quantile = 5, it goes long on the top 20% and short on the bottom 20% after sorting). To get these, it uses:
```python
quantile: int = int(len(slope) / self.quantile)
long: List[Tuple[Symbol, float]] = sorted_by_slope[:quantile]
short: List[Tuple[Symbol, float]] = sorted_by_slope[-quantile:]
```
Then, count how many entries are in each strategy, and use 1/n weighting in the longs and the shorts:
```python 
long_count: int = len(long)
short_count: int = len(short)

long_w: float = 1 / long_count
short_w: float = 1 / short_count
```
Lastly, we place the buy / sell orders as follows (for a stock in the long section):
- get the symbol for that stock / underlying
- get the current price
- If all the data necessary for trading is present:
    - Set equity_amount = long_w * the current total portfolio value of the strategy
    - Set options_amount = int(equity/(price * 100)) - this is the number of options to buy. It's divided by the price * 100 as options have 100x leverage. 
    - Buy options_amount of the short atm call 
    - Sell options_amount * 50 of the underlying - this delta hedges our position, as delta is 0.5 = 50/100.
    - Save our trades to a dict that stores opened positions.

For a stock in the short section a similar process happens but with the relevant parts flipped.

We'll be covering this strategy in a CUATS Coding Session in Michaelmas term, where we'll go through it in much more detail.



### 8.2.2 - Performance

Performed relatively well in 2017-2021 (which is out of sample for the paper) in terms of overall P&L, however almost all of this return was generated in a single month. This is likely not desirable. In the more recent period of 2021-2024 it also had a large spike, this time roughly doubling, however in 2023 and 2024 it lost a significant amount of money and overall lost 60% across the three years, primarily from it's poor performance in 2024.

If you are unable to find options data, check yfinance version 0.2.40 is the most current version, and if not update to the current one. To update in conda, one may need to use the following: conda install -c conda-forge yfinance=0.2.40=pyhd8ed1ab_0).

- Pandas(2.2.2) - https://pandas.pydata.org/, a library that provides fast DataFrame objects which we'll use for storing data. Plotly and yfinance both use Pandas so using it makes it easier to interface with them. (Install instructions: https://pandas.pydata.org/getting_started.html)

- Plotly(5.22.0) - https://plotly.com/python/, a library that makes producing high quality plots easy. We'll use this for making visualisations of volatility surfaces. (Install instructions: https://plotly.com/python/getting-started/)

- Matplotlib(3.9.1) - https://matplotlib.org/, the standard python plotting library. Only used for a single plot which can't be easily replicated in plotly, so this is optional. (Install instructions: https://matplotlib.org/stable/install/index.html)

- nbformat(5.10.4) - https://pypi.org/project/nbformat/, the base Jupyter notebook format, sometimes the Plotly plots won't show unless this package is installed.

- ipykernel(6.29.5) - https://pypi.org/project/ipykernel/, a package that is needed to run Jupyter Notebooks. For a brief introduction to Jupyter Notebooks, see: https://jupyter.org/try-jupyter/notebooks/?path=notebooks/Intro.ipynb

There are also some other libraries we'll import (datetime and os) but these are standard python libraries and don't need to be installed.
